{"type":"message","id":"7af6f6f9","parentId":"87bd2463","timestamp":"2026-05-02T02:42:47.379Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Bobby wants to be updated after each video is completed. Let me set up a sub-agent task to handle the transcription work, and I'll relay updates to Bobby after each video.\n\nActually, given there could be 30+ videos, using sub-agents in parallel might be the most efficient approach. But Bobby wants updates after each video. Let me think about the best approach:\n\n1. Single-threaded - I'd do one at a time, report after each. Slow but accurate.\n2. Parallel sub-agents - I'd spawn multiple in parallel, they'd complete faster, but updates would come in batches.\n\nGiven the importance of accuracy here (the last batch had mismatched transcripts), I think a more deliberate approach is better. \n\nI'm leaning toward parallel sub-agents for speed but with careful verification built in—each sub-agent would transcribe its assigned videos and report back after completing each one so Bobby stays informed of progress.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Given the importance of accuracy and the fact that we're redoing everything from scratch, I should be more systematic about this. Let me set up a workflow where I use sub-agents to process multiple videos at once but they report completion after each one so I can relay those updates to Bobby. I'll need to extract all the video URLs first, then organize them by upload date to know the chronological order before assigning work to sub-agents.\n\nThe most efficient approach would be to extract the full video list with upload dates first, then spawn sub-agents for each video with clear instructions to report back after completing each transcript so I can keep Bobby updated in real time.\n\nI could work through the list sequentially myself—open each video URL in Chrome, transcribe and summarize it, save the file, report progress to Bobby, then move to the next one. This is methodical but time-intensive for what could be 30+ videos.\n\nAlternatively, I could batch the transcriptions by having sub-agents handle multiple videos per batch and report after each one completes, which would be faster. Given the volume, I think parallel batching makes the most sense, though I need to weigh that against Bobby's preference for frequent updates.\n\nThe key constraint is that each transcript needs to be verified for accuracy before moving forward. I can spawn sub-agents in parallel batches of 3-4 videos, and they'll report back after each one so I can update Bobby. Once all new batches are done, I'll spawn the next batch until we hit video Qkqe-uRhQJE, then I can clean up the old files.\n\nNow I'm going to start by browsing through Alex Finn's channel to extract all the video data. I'll compile everything into a numbered list organized chronologically from oldest to newest, confirm the stopping point, and save it to a file so we have a clear roadmap before the sub-agents begin their work.\n\nStarting the collection now.\n","thinkingSignature":"841ae7a838173cce602e0cd9f97c6f4f1a8b174de2edbfeed1939c8f36fe4298"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nYes Bobby — you'll hear from me after each video is done. Let me set up a structured plan and start working through it.\n\n**Here's my approach:**\n1. Extract all 247 videos (newest + oldest tabs) to get the full chronological list\n2. Filter to OpenClaw-only videos in chronological order\n3. Transcribe one at a time, report to you after each completion\n4. Only delete old files AFTER everything is verified correct\n\nLet me start by collecting the video list. Going now — first update coming after the first video is done."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":83088,"output":694,"cacheRead":192,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":83974,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1777689728688,"responseId":"0